---

When I set out to recreate the Duckquill aesthetic, I had several options: stick with Zola, use a popular framework like Next.js or Astro, or try something different. I chose SvelteKit, and here's why.

## Simplicity

Svelte's philosophy aligns perfectly with building a blog. There's no virtual DOM, no complex state management to learn—just write components that compile to efficient JavaScript.

```svelte
<script>
  let count = 0;
</script>

<button on:click={() => count++}>
  Clicked {count} times
</button>
```

That's it. No imports, no hooks, no ceremony.

## Performance

SvelteKit's static adapter generates pure HTML, CSS, and minimal JavaScript. The result is a blog that:

- Loads instantly
- Works without JavaScript (mostly)
- Scores 100 on Lighthouse

## Developer Experience

The tooling is excellent:

- Hot module replacement works flawlessly
- TypeScript support is first-class
- File-based routing is intuitive
- MDsveX handles Markdown beautifully

## Flexibility

Unlike static site generators that lock you into templates, SvelteKit gives you full control. Need an interactive component in a blog post? Just import it:

```markdown
---
title: My Interactive Post
---

<script>
  import MyChart from '$lib/components/MyChart.svelte';
</script>

Check out this chart:

<MyChart data={[1, 2, 3, 4, 5]} />
```

## The Verdict

For a simple blog, Zola or Hugo might be faster to set up. But if you want:

- Full control over your site's behavior
- The ability to add interactive elements
- A foundation that can grow with your needs

...SvelteKit is an excellent choice.

